title: User query: Plan description from client LLM
log: Make a Wayang Plan that take the cities in relevant municipalities textfile and returns all organisations which have a matching municipality in the textfile. The textfile only have cities so you need to check if the city is in the municipality column. Output the result in a textfile.

title: Agent: SpecifierAgent Output
log:
Create an Apache Wayang Plan that:
- Reads a text file named "relevant_municipality_cities.txt" containing city names (one city per line).
- Reads an organisations dataset (input source) that includes a "municipality" column.
- Filters the organisations to those whose "municipality" field contains any city from the cities file (i.e., the city string appears as a substring in the municipality column).
- Writes the filtered organisation records to an output text file.

log.thoughts: The plan needs the organisation table to match organisation.municipality against cities from the provided text file. The user referenced a textfile containing cities (cities_in_relevant_municipalities.txt), so I include it as an input source and the organisation table as the data source to filter. If the actual textfile name differs, include any similarly named textfile.

steps.detailed_description: Load two inputs: (a) the text file 'relevant_municipality_cities.txt' as a line-by-line text input (each line is a city name), and (b) the JDBC table 'organisation' including all columns (organisation_id, organisation_no, active_organisation, name, social_housing_org, municipality). Output: two input datasets (cities lines and organisation rows).

Match/filter organisation rows against the city list: for each organisation row, keep the row if its 'municipality' column contains any city string from the 'relevant_municipality_cities.txt' file (i.e., substring match). Input: the organisations dataset and the cities dataset (lines). Output: filtered organisations dataset containing only rows where municipality contains at least one city from the cities file. Note: this step conceptually represents the binary operation that combines the two inputs (e.g., a broadcast/filter-join or cross-filter using substring matching).

Write the filtered organisation records (all columns from the 'organisation' table for rows that matched) to an output text file. Use a line-oriented text output such as 'filtered_organisations.txt' (one organisation record per output line in a chosen serialization). Input: filtered organisations dataset. Output: 'filtered_organisations.txt'.

log.thoughts: Three steps keep the plan minimal: load both inputs, perform a binary match/filter where municipality contains any city substring, then write the filtered organisations to a text file.
